'''Sir Nalini Ranjan Chatterjee'''<ref>Also spelt Chatterji.</ref> (died 6 September 1942<ref>Biography, ''[[Who Was Who]]''</ref>) was a [[judge]] of the [[Calcutta High Court]], [[India]] from 1910 to 1926 and officiated as Chief Justice on three occasions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://calcuttahighcourt.nic.in/sesqui/val4.pdf|title=Name of the Chief Justices & Judges of the High Court at Calcutta|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=134|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> He was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the New Year Honours in 1920.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=31712 |date=30 December 1919 |page=3 |supp=y}}</ref> He became a member of the [[Viceroy's Executive Council]] post retirement.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=|title=Nalini Ranjan's Portrait Unveiled|last=|first=|date=24 December 2001|newspaper=Statesman|access-date=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|work=|via=}}</ref>

It was said of Chatterjee by then [[George Claus Rankin|Chief Justice Rankin]] that not a single judgment of the former was set aside by the [[Judicial Committee of the Privy Council|Privy Council]].<ref name=":0" />

[[File:Nalini ranjan chatterjee residence.jpg|thumb|Chatterjee's residence in Nabogram, 30 km before [[Santiniketan]] en route from Calcutta.]]

